Soooooo good!!! Went here for dinner last night. It was my birthday (woot woot!) Right around the corner from our hotel, and we were seated immediately. Something I completely didn't expect on a Friday night. Small, busy place but a nice, cosy atmosphere. Had read up on it a bit before we got there so I knew to get the crawfish beignets. BEST PART OF THE MEAL OK?! Got two of those and we LOVED them. Got the crouton salad with fried cheese. Really good. Nice balance of sweet and salty and bitter. Yumm. Main course was shrimp and grits. Took a bit of time, because they ran out and had to make a fresh batch, but the staff was so nice and even came and apologized even though it really wasn't taking that long! First time having grits and it was AMAZING!!! Personally I liked the caramelized onions and bacon more than the shrimp, which didn't seem to add much flavor to the dish, and would have liked to have more of that, but that's just my opinion. Now at this point, mom and I are SO full. The portions were ENORMOUS. But, like, it's my birthday. And I gotta have something sweet. So I got a chocolate filled beignet a la carte, because there's no way I'm eating three of those bad boys. And just... I love chocolate. And this was like... Unf. I think it was dark chocolate in it, which is gr9 because I prefer dark chocolate, and that slight bitterness combatting the sweetness made the whole thing so delicious. And another point in their favor, the staff added a nice candle to my plate without being asked just because we said it was my birthday. Overall an amazing experience. Would recommend 10/10 times.

Review for an on-going experience since September 3, 2011. A good thing is always worth the wait. Brenda's, bustling with an excitement that almost bursts the restaurant at its seams, captures the sprit of that rule. I suggested this place as a first date to a gentleman I had met only days before, assuring him that though we may wait long, the food definitely made up for it. As my date and I nervously began our first real conversation, we had two whole hours to discern if we each truly wanted the other as table company. We discussed everything under the sun, our conversation natural and refreshing. Those two hours flew by in no time, and as the tantalizing smells of the kitchen and the warm vibe inside spilled onto the sidewalk, we were ready to eat. When finally they called us inside, I gently warned him: "this food is SO good we may not say anything to each other while we eat. This is going to have to be okay with you..." We said not a word to each other as we ate the following: -apple beignets -watermelon iced tea -fried chicken -eggs benedict on a heavenly biscuit No matter where we go, we've since called any time we eat food that absolutely FLOORS us, a "Brenda's Moment." As we plan our wedding, guests may very well find Brenda's catered goodies on their plates, as they have a special place in our stomachs and in our hearts. What else can I say? A good thing is always worth the wait.

Wonderful to have a spot for inexpensive, but good, food like you might find in the neighborhood back streets of New Orleans, or "Anywhere, Louisiana," for that matter. This was my 1st time here. Having grown up in the South, I have a lifelong appreciation for -- and strong opinions about -- this kind of food. Here's my take: Collard greens - dictionary definition of excellent! Very flavorful, yet not too meaty or greasy. Cooked perfectly. Bravo! Shrimp with Grits - Delicious, but not excellent. Too creamy, long stringy cheese, not enough texture of the grits. Grits for toddlers. I want to know my food. I want to feel the corn's texture, "to the tooth," not for it to hide unnoticed in its creamy, cheesy medium. Nice flavors, though. Wine Glasses - Please lose the grade school juice glass filled to the rim. This is a cheesy (OK, pun intended) "because we're a 'homestyle' restaurant" affectation, and a way to conceal a mediocre wine's lack of aroma and flavor characteristics, but why do this? Serving even really fine wine this way ensures that it'll leave an impression of flavorless mediocrity because it suppresses any aroma and flavor characteristics the wine may have. While "grown ups'" wine glassware would cost more, it would probably sell more 2nd glasses of wine. Overall, "Very Good," and I will return to try more dishes. But, perhaps I'll stick with beer next time.

Great food. Stopped by for breakfast. - Shrimp and Grits: great dish. It tastes a lot better than it looks and is probably the best shrimp and grits I've ever had. - Crawfish beignet: good stuff. Mine wasn't dry as I'd read in a few other reviews. I'd probably get it again. - Apple beignet: this was enjoyable but I probably wouldn't get it again. I felt like the inside was too "dry" in the sense that it was just filled with cooked apples and had no "sauce". - Sweet watermelon iced tea: interesting spin on sweet tea. I liked it. The portions are rather large, so I left full after splitting the shrimp and grits, eating a whole crawfish beignet, and splitting an apple beignet. You can mix and match the beignets however you feel like, so don't feel locked in to ordering 3 of the same or trying one of each in the sampler. This place gets quite busy so keep that in mind. I was able to get seated within 10 minutes when I arrived ~10am on a Friday morning, but the waiting list got pretty long by the time I got up to leave an hour later. And although the menu makes this place seem like it would be great for groups, I'd recommend going as a party of two, and no larger than a party of four due to the limited seating. I was able to jump ahead of a couple larger parties that were ahead of me on the waiting list as a result. Also, they had a bunch of specials written on chalkboards on the wall that are not on the printed menu not posted online.

    Wonderful to have a spot for inexpensive, but good, food like you might find in the neighborhood back streets of New Orleans, or "Anywhere, Louisiana," for that matter. This was my 1st time here.  Having grown up in the South, I have a lifelong appreciation for -- and strong opinions about -- this kind of food.  Here's my take:  

    Collard greens - dictionary definition of excellent! Very flavorful, yet not too meaty or greasy. Cooked perfectly. Bravo!

    Shrimp with Grits - Delicious, but not excellent.  Too creamy, long stringy cheese, not enough texture of the grits. Grits for toddlers.  I want to know my food.  I want to feel the corn's texture, "to the tooth," not for it to hide unnoticed in its creamy, cheesy medium.  Nice flavors, though.

    Wine Glasses - Please lose the grade school juice glass filled to the rim. This is a cheesy (OK, pun intended) "because we're a 'homestyle' restaurant" affectation, and a way to conceal a mediocre wine's lack of aroma and flavor characteristics, but why do this?

    Serving even really fine wine this way ensures that it'll leave an impression of flavorless mediocrity because it suppresses any aroma and flavor characteristics the wine may have.  While "grown ups'" wine glassware would cost more, it would probably sell more 2nd glasses of wine.

    Overall, "Very Good," and I will return to try more dishes. But, perhaps I'll stick with beer next time.

    8/5/2016

    Great food. Stopped by for breakfast.

    - Shrimp and Grits: great dish. It tastes a lot better than it looks and is probably the best shrimp and grits I've ever had.
    - Crawfish beignet: good stuff. Mine wasn't dry as I'd read in a few other reviews. I'd probably get it again.
    - Apple beignet: this was enjoyable but I probably wouldn't get it again. I felt like the inside was too "dry" in the sense that it was just filled with cooked apples and had no "sauce".
    - Sweet watermelon iced tea: interesting spin on sweet tea. I liked it.

    The portions are rather large, so I left full after splitting the shrimp and grits, eating a whole crawfish beignet, and splitting an apple beignet. You can mix and match the beignets however you feel like, so don't feel locked in to ordering 3 of the same or trying one of each in the sampler.

    This place gets quite busy so keep that in mind. I was able to get seated within 10 minutes when I arrived ~10am on a Friday morning, but the waiting list got pretty long by the time I got up to leave an hour later.

    And although the menu makes this place seem like it would be great for groups, I'd recommend going as a party of two, and no larger than a party of four due to the limited seating. I was able to jump ahead of a couple larger parties that were ahead of me on the waiting list as a result.

    Also, they had a bunch of specials written on chalkboards on the wall that are not on the printed menu not posted online.

The original beignet is as good as café du monde and the  flight which featues sweet and savory fillings is a great appetizer or dessert.  Classics like the shrimp and grits for breakfast or the fried chicken and fries are as good as I've had anywhere. This is easily one of the best restaurants in the City. If you like New Orleans style food, don't bypass Brendas
